{
  "local_port": 47460,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "A shop was selling 3 chocolates for Re. 1 and if you return three wrappers you get 1 free. If so, how many chocolates can you get for Rs. 45?",
  "response": "To determine the total number of chocolates you can get for Re. 45, considering both the initial purchase and the free chocolates obtained by returning wrappers, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Initial Purchase:**\n   - **Price:** 3 chocolates for Re. 1.\n   - **Chocolates for Re. 45:** \n     \\[\n     45 \\text{ rupees} \\times 3 \\text{ chocolates per rupee} = 135 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Wrappers Obtained:** 135 wrappers.\n\n2. **First Exchange:**\n   - **Exchange Rate:** 3 wrappers for 1 free chocolate.\n   - **Free Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     \\frac{135 \\text{ wrappers}}{3} = 45 \\text{ free chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Total Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     135 + 45 = 180 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Wrappers Now:** 45 wrappers (from the free chocolates).\n\n3. **Second Exchange:**\n   - **Free Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     \\frac{45 \\text{ wrappers}}{3} = 15 \\text{ free chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Total Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     180 + 15 = 195 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Wrappers Now:** 15 wrappers.\n\n4. **Third Exchange:**\n   - **Free Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     \\frac{15 \\text{ wrappers}}{3} = 5 \\text{ free chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Total Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     195 + 5 = 200 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Wrappers Now:** 5 wrappers.\n\n5. **Fourth Exchange:**\n   - **Free Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     \\frac{5 \\text{ wrappers}}{3} = 1 \\text{ free chocolate} \\quad (\\text{with 2 wrappers remaining})\n     \\]\n   - **Total Chocolates:** \n     \\[\n     200 + 1 = 201 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n   - **Wrappers Now:** 1 wrapper (cannot exchange further as you need at least 3).\n\n**Final Answer:** You can obtain a total of **201 chocolates** for Re. 45.",
